would hide something like that.

17:11.448 --> 17:14.360
HeHo,Lance.
Don’t hover.
You can come in.

17:14.451 --> 17:16.658
Oh. I wasn’t—
I wasn’t hovering.

17:16.745 --> 17:18.235
ljust— I didn’t
want to interrupt you...

17:18.330 --> 17:20.195
if you were in
the middle of something.

17:20.290 --> 17:21.405
Too late.
How can I help you?

17:21.499 --> 17:24.957
Uh, l—
Well, you know,

17:25.045 --> 17:26.785
H was in the lab.

17:26.880 --> 17:28.916
We haven’t seen
each other since—

17:29.007 --> 17:31.919
Since, you know—
Since we last saw
each other, and—

17:32.052 --> 17:34.964
How are you?
Good. I’m good.
How you doing?

17:35.055 --> 17:37.512
l’m reexamining
Rachel Knox’s X—rays,

17:37.599 --> 17:39.214
hoping to find leads
toward a murder weapon.

17:39.351 --> 17:41.592
Actually, I meant—
In doing so,
I realized the fracture...

17:41.686 --> 17:43.517
to the right side
of her nasal bone is remodeled.

17:43.605 --> 17:45.937
And that means that about
six months before her death,

17:46.024 --> 17:47.980
Rachel Knox sustained
a blow to the face.

17:48.068 --> 17:50.150
Cool.
Actually, when | asked
how you were doing,

17:50.237 --> 17:54.401
I meant you personally,
not you in the case.

17:54.491 --> 17:56.402
I don’t think
there’s any real need
for that conversation.

17:56.493 --> 17:58.404
Sure, there is.

17:58.495 --> 18:00.406
We were part
of each other’s lives
for a long time.

18:00.497 --> 18:02.829
What are we?
Supposed to just stop?

18:02.958 --> 18:06.075
I don’t know. This is
my first serious breakup.
Yeah, me too.

18:06.169 --> 18:09.252
But I don’t think
we—we have to stop
talking to each other.

18:09.339 --> 18:10.875
I mean, I don’t know.

18:10.966 --> 18:12.331
Have you found
a place to live yet?

18:12.425 --> 18:13.961
I’m staying
in the apartment
you found for us.

18:14.094 --> 18:16.005
Nice.
It’s working out
very well.

18:16.096 --> 18:18.929
I hear you’re still living
with Dr. Brennan
and Agent Booth.

18:19.015 --> 18:22.348
Mmm. Little bit,
temporarily.

18:22.435 --> 18:25.097
Also, I’m writing a paper
on asymmetrical bilateral
fracturing...

18:25.188 --> 18:27.520
of pubic tubercles in
late surgical separation...

18:27.607 --> 18:29.848
of postmedieval
conjoined twins
in Sighisoara, Romania.

18:29.943 --> 18:31.979
Wow. Nice.
Well done.

18:32.070 --> 18:36.109
l, uh— Hey, I had a paper
on body symmetry
and cognition...

18:36.199 --> 18:38.485
published in the Annual Review
of Psychology, so—

18:38.618 --> 18:41.530
I know. Congratulations.
How did you know?

18:41.621 --> 18:44.704
You credited me,
which was very nice.

18:44.791 --> 18:49.410
Everything I learned
about body symmetry,
I learned... from you.

18:49.504 --> 18:51.210
Very generous of you,
Lance.

18:51.298 --> 18:53.254
Now, I must get these
details to Dr. Brennan.

18:53.341 --> 18:57.004
— It was good seeing you.
- Yeah, it’s nice to—

18:57.095 --> 18:58.881
nice to be working
with you again.

19:02.058 --> 19:03.594
I didn’t tell you
about me and Rachel...

19:03.685 --> 19:05.801
becauseits—
it’s practically
ancient history.

19:05.895 --> 19:09.353
I doubt that.
Ancient history began
over 5,000 years ago,

19:09.441 --> 19:11.397
stops at the beginning
of the Middle Ages.

19:11.484 --> 19:12.985
Rachel and I broke up
nearly a year ago.

19:13.069 --> 19:14.570
It doesn’t mean
anything anymore,

19:14.654 --> 19:16.485
and it has nothing to do
with what happened to her.

19:16.573 --> 19:18.279
The thing is,
you don’t get
to decide any of that.

19:18.366 --> 19:20.982
[ Brennan ]
By “nearly a year ago,”
do you mean seven months?

19:21.077 --> 19:22.533
Yeah, yeah, seven months
sounds about right.

19:22.620 --> 19:26.738
That’s around the time
someone smashed her
in the face.

19:27.917 --> 19:29.873
I would never do that.

19:31.087 --> 19:32.918
Not on purpose.

19:33.006 --> 19:36.089
Right, so you ace/denla/ly
smashed her in the face.

19:39.554 --> 19:40.760
This is embarrassing.
Embarrassing?

19:40.847 --> 19:44.180
I’m thinking more
“incriminating,”
so spit it out.

19:44.267 --> 19:49.136
- Rachel is—
was a tantric master.
- Tantric sex?

19:49.230 --> 19:50.811
Bones, there’s got to be
other kinds of—

19:50.899 --> 19:52.810
— Yes, tantric sex.
— Okay, carry on.

19:52.901 --> 19:55.893
During one of
our... sessions, I fell.

19:55.987 --> 19:57.102
I got tired, I slipped,

19:57.197 --> 19:59.904
l was shifting my position,
and my elbow hit her.

20:00.033 --> 20:03.617
It’s the stupidest
thing I’ve ever heard.
It’s understandable.

20:03.703 --> 20:08.367
A successful tantric session
lasts seven, eight hours
and can cause extreme,

20:08.458 --> 20:10.699
sometimes painful,
muscle fatigue.

20:10.794 --> 20:13.376
Or she wanted out, he didn’t,
then something snapped.

20:13.463 --> 20:16.045
- No, I knew Rachel’s policy
up front.
— What kind of policy?

20:16.174 --> 20:19.837
Rachel had a three—month maximum
with a guy,
and then she moved on.

20:19.928 --> 20:22.510
She wanted fabulous sex,
spiritual connection,

20:22.597 --> 20:24.053
no strings.

20:24.140 --> 20:25.471
So you were only with her
for three months?

20:25.558 --> 20:27.640
Best three months
of my life.

20:27.727 --> 20:29.137
Then what? You went back
to business as usual?

20:29.270 --> 20:31.727
That was the arrangement.
It’s often
quite difficult...

20:31.815 --> 20:33.680
for a man to accord
to a woman’s rules,

20:33.775 --> 20:36.642
especially when rather
exquisite sex is involved.

20:36.736 --> 20:38.317
Look, I had my time
with Rachel.

20:38.405 --> 20:39.986
We were something,
then she moved on,

20:40.073 --> 20:42.155
and we went back
to being what
we always were—

20:42.242 --> 20:45.154
good friends
and business partners.

20:45.995 --> 20:48.737
Death business.

20:48.832 --> 20:50.914
Look, do you mind?
I have to get back to work.

20:51.000 --> 20:53.161
Losing Rachel has
left me shorthanded.

20:58.842 --> 21:02.175
[ Daisy ]
Dr. Saroyan.
I’ve made a startling discovery.

21:02.262 --> 21:05.425
— Let’s hear it.
- Monica Craig died of
lung cancer, correct?

21:05.515 --> 21:07.756
Yes. It metastasized
to her brain...

21:07.851 --> 21:09.557
and to her spine,
amongst other areas.

21:09.644 --> 21:11.805
May I commandeer
your computer?

21:19.487 --> 21:22.354
This shows bone metastasis
in the femur.

21:22.449 --> 21:24.656
Why don’t we justjump
to the startling discovery?

21:24.742 --> 21:26.278
I don’t think
Monica Craig’s cancer...

21:26.369 --> 21:28.234
was advanced enough
to cause actual death.

21:28.329 --> 21:29.865
What?

21:29.956 --> 21:32.242
I believe she had
weeks left to live
at the time of her death.

21:32.375 --> 21:35.117
Perhaps even months.
That is a startling discovery.

21:35.211 --> 21:37.463
We have no apparent
cause of death
for Monica Craig.

21:37.547 --> 21:40.129
Because we blamed it
on the cancer.

21:40.258 --> 21:42.044
Good job, Ms. Wick.
I know.

21:44.512 --> 21:46.673
So, using the info
that Daisy gave us,

21:46.764 --> 21:49.927
Hodgins and l have been
working together to try
to narrow down the weapon...

21:50.018 --> 21:51.929
that was used to create
the kill—shot wound.

21:53.688 --> 21:56.475
So I took a 3—D impression
of the wound to the sternum...

21:56.566 --> 21:58.807
to create an image,
which gives us—

22:00.320 --> 22:01.856
That’s a very
distinctive pattern.

22:01.946 --> 22:04.107
Scrapings contained
particulates of amazonite.

22:04.199 --> 22:06.110
It’s a stone indigenous
to this area.

22:06.201 --> 22:08.692
I checked the database to see
if there were any stone weapons...

22:08.786 --> 22:11.277
that could create
a similar wound pattern.

22:12.499 --> 22:14.035
[ Brennan ]
All ancient weapons.

22:14.125 --> 22:15.911
[ Hodgins ]
Yes, but do not despair,

22:16.002 --> 22:20.166
because the stone contained
microscopic particles
of diamonds, which means—

22:20.256 --> 22:22.542
— Saws.
— Yeah,
I also found cutting oil.

22:22.634 --> 22:27.003
So, the weapon was a cut rock,
sourced locally.

22:27.096 --> 22:29.428
A stone,
a—a burial marker.

22:29.516 --> 22:33.885
And Mirza makes all
of the burial markers for
Green Passages. Well done.

22:33.978 --> 22:37.937
Now we know
the victim was crushed
by a stone burial marker.

22:38.024 --> 22:40.481
And we know who made it.
[ Exhales ]

22:49.035 --> 22:51.242
[ Booth ] You know,
everything just keeps
coming back to you.

22:51.371 --> 22:54.363
You forget to mention something.
We find out about it.
We dig a little bit more,

22:54.457 --> 22:56.118
and then, hey, boom,
there’s something else.

22:56.209 --> 22:58.746
I lost my partner,
Agent Booth.

22:58.836 --> 23:00.337
I’m sorry
if my thoughts are muddled.

23:00.421 --> 23:03.288
Memory loss from grief
is quite common.

23:03.383 --> 23:04.418
And convenient.

23:04.509 --> 23:07.922
In your catalog, it says
that you hand—carve...

23:08.012 --> 23:10.003
all of the grave markers
for your clients.

23:10.098 --> 23:11.588
Yes. That is part
of our service.

23:11.724 --> 23:14.431
lncluding Mrs. Craig’s?
Yes. That was
a beautiful marker.

23:14.519 --> 23:16.976
— l carved the symbol chi.
- The Chinese symbol
for life—force.

23:17.063 --> 23:20.555
It meant a lot to her.
It was carved
from a local stone slab.

23:20.650 --> 23:23.107
I can give you
its dimensions
and its weight.

23:23.194 --> 23:24.775
I don’t want to leave
anything out this time.

23:24.904 --> 23:27.771
Grief really makes you
a smart—ass too.
No. No, no, no.

23:27.865 --> 23:31.278
That comes
from being repeatedly accused
of a crime I did not commit.

23:33.454 --> 23:36.912
We may not have
been intimate anymore,

23:37.000 --> 23:38.490
but I loved Rachel.

23:38.585 --> 23:40.075
Oh, I believe you loved her.

23:40.169 --> 23:42.160
But she ended the affair,
which made you really angry.

23:42.297 --> 23:46.290
[ Brennan ]
You should know that the marker
you placed on the grave...

23:46.426 --> 23:49.008
is headed for the lab
at the Jeffersonian.
What?

23:49.095 --> 23:52.553
Wait. You think someone used
the marker to kill Rachel?

23:52.640 --> 23:55.256
When a killer bludgeons someone
that violently,

23:55.351 --> 23:57.558
he usually leaves
behind some D.N.A.

23:57.645 --> 24:01.012
Oh, okay, so I can
expect you guys again
asking for a DNA. sample.

24:01.107 --> 24:03.098
Oh, but that
shouldn’t matter to you,
’cause you’re innocent, right?

24:03.192 --> 24:04.443
Yeah, that is right,
actually, but you know what?

24:04.527 --> 24:07.815
Just to be on the safe side,
I’m gonna consult an attorney.

24:19.292 --> 24:21.999
Dr. Hodgins,
everything all right?

24:22.086 --> 24:23.951
You’re not mad
at your beetles, are you?

24:24.047 --> 24:25.753
No. Maybe a little disappointed.

24:25.840 --> 24:27.831
But, no, l was just thinking
about what Daisy said—

24:27.925 --> 24:30.132
that Monica Craig’s cancer
wouldn’t have killed her yet.

24:30.219 --> 24:33.382
Cancer metastasizes differently
in every person.

24:33.473 --> 24:35.839
We’ll be running
more tests though.

24:37.060 --> 24:38.925
I want to be
shot into the sun.

24:39.020 --> 24:40.806
— Uh, what?
— When I die.

24:40.897 --> 24:44.105
I want to be loaded
into a spacecraft
and shot into the sun.

24:44.192 --> 24:45.432
Return to the source.

24:45.526 --> 24:48.142
You’re not expecting me
to arrange that
though,yeah?

24:48.237 --> 24:50.319
- No, I got it covered.
Thank you.
- Okay.

24:50.406 --> 24:52.146
How about you?
How do you want to go out?

24:52.241 --> 24:54.698
I am not
going in the ground,
that’s for damn sure.

24:54.786 --> 24:57.528
Ooh. I’ve hit a chord.
Why is that?

24:57.622 --> 25:00.910
Eleanor Marks,
New York, May 1994.

25:01.000 --> 25:03.616
— Is that one of your cases?
- It wasn’t my fault,
thank goodness.

25:03.711 --> 25:05.326
She was pronounced dead
by a colleague.

25:05.421 --> 25:08.037
But when the pallbearers
were carrying her coffin
to her grave,

25:08.132 --> 25:09.747
they heard scratching.

25:09.842 --> 25:12.709
— She was alive?
- It turns out,
she’d been in a coma,

25:12.804 --> 25:14.795
which is why I’m going
cremation all the way.

25:14.889 --> 25:17.551
| get it. Although you might
want to think about the sun.

25:19.602 --> 25:21.843
Oh, my God.
Look at this.

25:22.647 --> 25:24.137
At what
specifically?

25:24.232 --> 25:26.393
Here.

25:27.777 --> 25:30.143
Look at this.
They’re different sizes.

25:30.238 --> 25:31.728
See these guys?

25:31.823 --> 25:34.155
They’re growing
at a rate that’s considered
normal for beetles, right?

25:34.242 --> 25:37.609
— But the others—
- Oh, their gross, wormy
bellies are swollen.

25:37.704 --> 25:41.162
Exactly. They’re obese,
which is entomologically
impossible.

25:41.249 --> 25:44.662
See, beetles have protein
receptors that prevent them
from overeating,

25:44.752 --> 25:46.208
but something
interfered with that.

25:46.295 --> 25:47.956
They might be able
to tell us how she died.

25:48.047 --> 25:49.958
— Hey, do you know
where the coffee grinder is?
— Why is that?

25:50.049 --> 25:53.132
Well, the blender’s broken.
I’m gonna have to grind up
these little blimps,

25:53.219 --> 25:55.255
find out what gave ’em
an eating disorder.

25:55.346 --> 25:58.509
You’ll be replacing the coffee
grinder with a new one, yes?

26:01.144 --> 26:02.759
[ Booth ]
You know what?
I don’t like this guy Akshay.

26:02.895 --> 26:06.183
ljust don’t like him.
I think we should bring in
Dr. Craig and talk to him again.

26:06.274 --> 26:08.936
When his wife was dying,
he dealt with
both Akshay Mirza...

26:09.026 --> 26:10.857
and Rachel
before she was murdered.

26:10.945 --> 26:13.402
Okay, so you’re thinking
that he may have noticed
some friction between them?

26:13.489 --> 26:15.229
Oh, definitely. You know,
small things he saw...

26:15.324 --> 26:17.485
that might appear
to be meaningless
could have great meaning.

26:17.577 --> 26:20.068
All right, tell you what.
I will give him a call.

26:20.204 --> 26:22.695
Booth, l have a question.
You know what?
Am I gonna regret this?

26:22.832 --> 26:24.493
Well,
when I saw Daisy today—
No! No, no.

26:24.625 --> 26:26.240
No.
You didn’t let me finish.

26:26.335 --> 26:27.996
I don’t have to.
The answer is no.

26:28.087 --> 26:30.419
It’s not about us
getting back together, okay?
It’s about me.

26:30.506 --> 26:35.045
No. Whatever you’re thinking
right now, just— just
get it out of your mind.

26:35.136 --> 26:37.218
If you’ll just
hear—hear me out.
I realized—

26:37.305 --> 26:39.967
No. Make no decisions
based on seeing Daisy,
understand? No.

26:40.099 --> 26:41.680
Getting an apartment?
No!

26:41.768 --> 26:43.178
’Cause you’d
get the wrong place
for the wrong reasons.

26:43.269 --> 26:45.305
— If you’d just let me talk!
- No, I’m not gonna let you talk.

26:45.396 --> 26:47.978
Just get it out of your mind.
You understand?
You need two weeks,

26:48.065 --> 26:50.226
and one good night
of getting drunk.

26:50.318 --> 26:53.151
All right? Look,
that’s what you need,
so you can think straight.

26:53.279 --> 26:55.019
But—
These are scientific facts.
No. The answer is no.

26:55.156 --> 26:57.442
But—
This conversation is over.
I’m gonna call the husband.

26:57.533 --> 26:59.273
Bye—bye.
No. Out of your mind.

27:03.372 --> 27:06.785
